
DAY 18: JENKINS PIPELINE (Corrected)
PIPELINE:
	• Step-by-step execution of a particular process.
	• Pipelines are syntax-based.
	• We use the Groovy language to write pipelines.
	• It is a DSL (Domain Specific Language).
	• It provides a visualization of the process.
FLOW: CODE $\rightarrow$ BUILD $\rightarrow$ TEST $\rightarrow$ ARTIFACT $\rightarrow$ DEPLOY

TYPES:
	1. Scripted (Older, more flexible/complex Groovy)
	2. Declarative (Modern, stricter, and easier to read)

1. BASIC DECLARATIVE SYNTAX
Groovy

pipeline {
    agent any
    stages {
        stage('one') {
            steps {
                // Actions go here
            }
        }
    }
}
	• P — pipeline (The root block)
	• A — agent (Where to run the build)
	• S — stages (The container for all stages)
	• S — stage (The specific phase, e.g., 'Build')
	• S — step (The actual command, e.g., sh 'mvn...')

2. MULTI-STAGE PIPELINE
Best for visualization and troubleshooting.
Groovy

pipeline {
    agent any
    stages {
        stage('Checkout') {
            steps {
                git 'https://github.com/devops/jenkins.git'
            }
        }
        stage('Build') {
            steps {
                sh 'mvn compile'
            }
        }
        stage('Test') {
            steps {
                sh 'mvn test'
            }
        }
        stage('Artifact') {
            steps {
                sh 'mvn clean package'
            }
        }
    }
}

3. PIPELINE AS CODE (Single Shell Optimization)
Use this when you want to run multiple commands in one session using triple quotes (''').
Groovy

pipeline {
    agent any
    stages {
        stage('Build & Package') {
            steps {
                git 'https://github.com/devops/jenkins.git'
                sh '''
                mvn compile
                mvn test
                mvn package
                mvn install
                mvn clean package
                '''
            }
        }
    }
}

4. MULTI-COMMAND / MULTI-STAGE
A hybrid approach where stages are grouped by logic.
Groovy

pipeline {
    agent any
    stages {
        stage('Source & Compile') {
            steps {
                git 'https://github.com/devops/jenkins.git'
                sh 'mvn compile'
            }
        }
        stage('Test & Package') {
            steps {
                sh 'mvn test'
                sh 'mvn clean package'
            }
        }
    }
}

